Measures the loss given an input tensor x x x and a labels tensor y y y (containing 1 or -1).
This is usually used for measuring whether two inputs are similar or
dissimilar, e.g. using the L1 pairwise distance as x x x , and is typically
used for learning nonlinear embeddings or semi-supervised learning.  The loss function for n n n -th sample in the mini-batch is  l n = { x n , if y n = 1 , max ⁡ { 0 , Δ − x n } , if y n = − 1 , l_n = \begin{cases}
    x_n, & \text{if}\; y_n = 1,\\
    \max \{0, \Delta - x_n\}, & \text{if}\; y_n = -1,
\end{cases} l n ​ = { x n ​ , max { 0 , Δ − x n ​ } , ​ if y n ​ = 1 , if y n ​ = − 1 , ​ and the total loss functions is  ℓ ( x , y ) = { mean ⁡ ( L ) , if reduction = ‘mean’; sum ⁡ ( L ) , if reduction = ‘sum’. \ell(x, y) = \begin{cases}
    \operatorname{mean}(L), & \text{if reduction} = \text{`mean';}\\
    \operatorname{sum}(L),  & \text{if reduction} = \text{`sum'.}
\end{cases} ℓ ( x , y ) = { mean ( L ) , sum ( L ) , ​ if reduction = ‘mean’; if reduction = ‘sum’. ​ where L = { l 1 , … , l N } ⊤ L = \{l_1,\dots,l_N\}^\top L = { l 1 ​ , … , l N ​ } ⊤ .

